BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20220721T000000Z
DTEND:20220721T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T022744Z
UID:7lqvkfs31a36lsp5bs7mb8a28a@google.com
CREATED:20220715T184913Z
DESCRIPTION:<html-blob><u></u><u></u>Part 2: Was <i>that </i>the Reckoning?
  Addressing anti-Black racism in the news industry<br><br>Register <a href=
 "https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdRqzSzI2n2d9YCEsSwTn1-pILQuuJkm9
 IUdTGBuMiX3B5nYA/viewform" id="ow728" __is_owner="true">here</a>. (If you r
 egistered for Part 1\, you don't need to re-register.)<br><p>Part 1 was a f
 ascinating conversation. <b>Nikole Hannah-Jones</b>\, creator of the 1619 P
 roject and long-time NewsGuild member at the New York Times Magazine\, addr
 essed why it is important to address anti-Black racism specifically\, why s
 he “stopped pretending” she was aspiring to be objective\, how the lack of 
 newsroom diversity affects what we cover\, who we quote\, and how all that 
 affects the way readers evaluate our integrity.</p><p><b>Erin B. Logan</b>\
 , national politics reporter for the Los Angeles Times\, and <b>Desiree Ste
 nnett</b>\, race and equity reporter for the Orlando Sentinel\, discussed h
 ow their experiences galvanized them to address racism in their newsrooms.<
 /p><p>The conversation\, which was moderated by NewsGuild of New York Presi
 dent <b>Susan DeCarava</b>\, was so engaging that attendees insisted that w
 e postpone planned breakout sessions to allow the big-group discussion to c
 ontinue.</p><p>In Part 2\, Erin will facilitate a discussion about our prog
 ram for change and her experience chairing the Guild’s Black caucus at the 
 L.A. Times. Desiree will lead a conversation about how and why we expose ma
 nagement’s dirty little secrets (like pay inequities and the lack of newsro
 om diversity) and build community coalitions.</p><p>Together\, we’ll identi
 fy next steps to combat anti-Black racism in our industry and how we can in
 crease Black leadership within our union and our workplaces.</p><u></u><u><
 /u></html-blob>
LAST-MODIFIED:20220715T185802Z
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Part 2: Was that the Reckoning? Addressing anti-Black racism in the
  news industry
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
