DTEND:20220428T003000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T022744Z
UID:3obhgd80v1di9ei8mssd7grbq6@google.com
CREATED:20220422T200529Z
DESCRIPTION:<p>Pay Studies conducted by NewsGuild members have exposed shoc
 king pay disparities impacting women and people of color at employers acros
 s the country. Come hear firsthand how Guild activists have facilitated pay
  studies and then used them to fight for greater pay equity and diversity d
 emands in our contract campaigns.</p><p><strong><b><a href="https://docs.go
 ogle.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScisKC4uSkBPtgGwWyuthuTFjtJhURWktD1AEhacMebFqg5Xg
 /viewform?usp=sf_link" id="ow1318" __is_owner="true"><b>REGISTER HERE</b></
 a></b></strong></p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20220422T200529Z
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Tackling Racist & Sexist Pay Practices in the Workplace
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20220701T000000Z
DTEND:20220701T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T022744Z
UID:4pd323n5ki678f9d8f4rcc038v@google.com
CREATED:20220715T184720Z
DESCRIPTION:Part 2: Was that the Reckoning? Addressing anti-Black racism in
  the news industry<br><br>Register <a href="https://docs.google.com/forms/d
 /e/1FAIpQLSdGBZmC9N7U4SIO8QeesR8H8gVe0Nq5IZRBoVK6jM2ICSkSzw/viewform" id="o
 w6174" __is_owner="true">here</a>. If you registered for Part 1\, you don't
  need to re-register.<br><br><p dir="ltr">Part 1 was a fascinating conversa
 tion. <b>Nikole Hannah-Jones</b>\, creator of the 1619 Project and long-tim
 e NewsGuild member at the New York Times Magazine\, addressed why it is imp
 ortant to address anti-Black racism specifically\, why she “stopped pretend
 ing” she was aspiring to be objective\, how the lack of newsroom diversity 
 affects what we cover\, who we quote\, and how all that affects the way rea
 ders evaluate our integrity.</p><p dir="ltr"><b>Erin B. Logan</b>\, nationa
 l politics reporter for the Los Angeles Times\, and <b>Desiree Stennett</b>
 \, race and equity reporter for the Orlando Sentinel\, discussed how their 
 experiences galvanized them to address racism in their newsrooms.</p><p dir
 ="ltr">The conversation\, which was moderated by NewsGuild of New York Pres
 ident <b>Susan DeCarava</b>\, was so engaging that attendees insisted that 
 we postpone planned breakout sessions to allow the big-group discussion to 
 continue.</p><p dir="ltr">In Part 2\, Erin will facilitate a discussion abo
 ut our program for change and her experience chairing the Guild’s Black cau
 cus at the L.A. Times. Desiree will lead a conversation about how and why w
 e expose management’s dirty little secrets (like pay inequities and the lac
 k of newsroom diversity) and build community coalitions.</p><p dir="ltr">To
 gether\, we’ll identify next steps to combat anti-Black racism in our indus
 try and how we can increase Black leadership within our union and our workp
 laces.</p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20220715T184720Z
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Part 2: Was that the Reckoning? Addressing anti-Black racism in the
  news industry
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
